## Summary

Added **Tiger Harbour (Fuvahmulah)** to the Maldives — the highest-value remaining coverage gap in my region (Indian/Med/Africa). It was listed in `coverage-gaps.json` (Fuvahmulah, mapped to `ari-atoll-maldives`) and not yet in our data.

**Why this site:** Fuvahmulah hosts the Indian Ocean's largest known resident tiger shark population (~400 documented individuals, 6–18 per dive year-round) and is one of the most-searched shark-diving destinations of the past decade. The bulk of the obvious coverage gaps in my region (MS Zenobia, Elphinstone, Dunraven, Carnatic, Giannis D, MV Rozi, Straits of Tiran) were already covered by earlier blitz runs.

**Facts verified** across PADI, Divernet, DiveSSI, Pelagic Divers, and Liquid Shark Divers: Tiger Harbour is a harbour-mouth plateau (8–12 m) with a wall dropping past 60 m at the island's southeast tip; water 27–29 °C; viz 25–35 m peak (Jan–Apr), dropping in the SW monsoon; tigers year-round, pelagic threshers + scalloped hammerheads Oct–Apr, oceanic mantas Mar–May; advanced/managed bait dive with strong currents; access via 1.5-hr domestic flight from Malé (MLE → FVM).

**Hero image:** set to `null`. Wikimedia's `Category:Fuvahmulah` holds only beach/landscape shots, and the only tiger shark photos on Commons are from the Bahamas/Hawaii/Australia. Per the rules, a generic off-site stand-in is worse than `null`, so I left it null rather than mislead.

The entry passed validation: 12 monthly condition blocks, 754-char description (no banned fluff words), no duplicate.

DONE: Tiger Harbour (Fuvahmulah) added successfully
